commitResults.messageBody:
The name fullCommand is misleading and may confuse readers, as it does
not refer to the full command, but only the argument part of the
command.

The parameter has been renamed to argumentString to better reflect
the variable it is supposed to hold, which is the argument part of
the command string.

commitResults.messageBody:
isExit is currently an abstract method of Command, which requires all
subclasses to implement it. This results in unwanted code duplication
as it has similar behavior amongst all subclasses.

isExit has been changed to a normal method of Command, which returns
false. Hence, only the ByeCommand would need to override the isExit
method in order to return true. isExit methods in the other Command
subclasses have been removed.

This is done to reduce code duplication when adding new commands, and
also make the code easily changeable when we need to change the
implementation of the isExit method.

tasks.txt is user generated data and may not be useful to others
collaborating on the same project.

commitResults.messageBody:
The command uses TaskList.addTodo to add a Todo to the task list.
However, this is insufficient for our needs as we may need to set the
attributes of the Todo before adding them to the task list. By calling
TaskList methods, we print extra output to the console.

We use the new TaskList.addTask method to add tasks/todo to the task
list instead.

By doing this, we can set attributes of the Todo before adding them
to the task list and prevent printing extra lines.

commitResults.messageBody:
Saving of Task string to file only inserts a divider when optional
arguments such as category are present. There is difficulty in
determining which optional argument a divider divides.

Task.toFile has been modified to insert blank dividers for optional
arguments, and thus the position of the divider corresponds to the
parameters passed to create new Tasks.

This allows optional arguments to be saved and re-parsed into a new
Task when the program is loaded.

commitResults.messageBody:
Command.execute takes in a single TaskList, which was sufficient for
passing in TaskLists, but there needs to be more parameters to add
for new type of ItemList.

The signature of execute has been updated to pass a EnumMap so that
multiple lists can be accessed from the same variable.

This is done so that additional lists can be added to the collection
and passed to the execute function without renaming and adding
parameters in all Command.execute functions.

commitResults.messageBody:
The Command takes in an EnumMap that is created and passed around by
Duke. This is not very OOP as we cannot define our own behaviors for
it. This results in a lot of code duplication in the Duke class, and
many variables being created and passed around as parameters. This makes
refactoring or changing things in the code base very difficult as this
way of coding increases coupling.

A Model class has been refactored and passed into the Command to execute
instead. This also allows us to define its own behaviors such as saving
and loading from the Storage class, and any methods that we would want
to add in the future.

This decouples the Storage class from the Duke class, and is only used
in a single Model class. We can add our own behaviors to the Model class
in the future without adding lots of extra parameters or creating new
objects and passing them around. This also makes the code adhere better
to OOP and SLAP principles.
